Othello User Manual
Introduction
This manual explains how to install, run, and use this project. 
The main Flask game provides a Windows XP-styled interface to play with.

Installation
1. Ensure Python is installed.
2. Go to the project directory in a terminal.
3. Install dependencies using:
   pip install -r requirements.txt

Running the Web Application
To start the web application, run:
   python flask_engine.py
Once the server is running, open your browser and visit:
   http://127.0.0.1:5000
The Othello interface will load and you can start playing!

Gameplay Instructions
• The game begins with the standard Othello starting 2x2 position in the centre.
• Click any valid board square to play a move.
• If a player tries to make an illegal move, a message will appear.
• If a player has no legal moves, the turn automatically passes.
• The game ends when both player have no legal moves.

Saving and Loading
• Click 'Save game' to store the current game.
• Click 'Load game' to restore a previous game.
• Saved state is stored in savegame.json.

Restarting the Game
Click the 'Restart game' button to reset the board to the initial starting layout.

Command-Line Version
To play the CLI version:
   python game_engine.py
This version follows the same rules using the shared logic in components.py. 
To play a move, enter coordinates in the provided format.

Testing
To run the tests of the code:
   python pytest

Documentation
All written documentation is located in the readme of this project.

API Overview
This Flask app uses a simple HTTP API that allows you to control an Othello game.
All requests are simple GET requests and return JSON.

Below is a brief description of the endpoints
• View UI: GET /
   Renders board HTML
• Make a move: GET /move?x=<col>&y=<row>
   Attempts to place piece for current player at (x, y)
• Save game: GET /save
   Saves the current game_state to a JSON on the server
• Load game: GET /load
   Loads from savegame.json if it exists
• Restart: GET /restart
   Restarts the game

Support
If any issues occur, ensure dependencies are installed correctly or restart the Flask server.

Have fun playing!
